Lewes, Sussex, England","Hythe, Kent, England":"Hythe, Kent, England","Maidstone, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Maidstone, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Whitefriars Church, Canterbury, Kent, England":"Canterbury, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Brockhill Manor, Saltwood, Kent, England":"Saltwood, Kent, England","of, Sussex, England":"Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Canterbury, Kent, England":"Canterbury, Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Criol","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Alberto, Hipolito, Luis, Eriberto, Jose, Luisa, Ramon, Ricardo.  French/Haitian Edwige, Fritz, Serge, Yvrose.","Catalan: from the old personal name <i>Oriol</i>, from Latin <i>Aureolus</i>.","Catalan and French: nickname, possibly for a flamboyant dresser or sweet singer, from Catalan and Old French <i>oriol</i> ‘oriole’ (from Latin <i>aureolus</i> ‘golden’), a species of bird of which the male has bright yellow and black plumage. As a surname of French origin it is also common in Haiti."],"variants":[{"name":"Oriel","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English and Old French female personal name <i>Oriold</i>, <i>Oriel</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Aurildis</i>, <i>Orieldis</i>, composed of elements meaning ‘fire’ + ‘strife’.","French (Vosges): nickname from Old French <i>oriel</i>, a variant of <i>oriol</i> ‘oriole’ (see   Oriol  )."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":0,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":25,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":38,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":47,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":92,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Criol Lady of Brockhull was born in 1290, in Maidstone, Kent, England, United Kingdom. She married Sir. Thomas Brockhull High Sheriff of Kent about 1319, in Sussex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1390, in Hythe, Kent, England, at the age of 100, and was buried in Canterbury, Kent, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1290–1390":"1290–1390","1320–1383":"1320–1383","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","May 1383":"mai 1383","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","Abt 1319":"umbes 1319","1390":"1390","1290":"1290","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Lewes, Sussex, England":"Lewes, Sussex, England","Hythe, Kent, England":"Hythe, Kent, England","Maidstone, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Maidstone, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Whitefriars Church, Canterbury, Kent, England":"Canterbury, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Brockhill Manor, Saltwood, Kent, England":"Saltwood, Kent, England","of, Sussex, England":"Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Canterbury, Kent, England":"Canterbury, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1290–1390":"1290–1390","1320–1383":"1320–1383","1337":"1337",